&lt;h1 class="relative group">The Meaning of Word Knowledge in Bhagwat Gita
&lt;div id="the-meaning-of-word-knowledge-in-bhagwat-gita" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#the-meaning-of-word-knowledge-in-bhagwat-gita" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>In the Sanskrit language, there is a word &amp;ldquo;ज्ञान&amp;rdquo; (romanized as Gyan or Jnyana), which translates to &amp;ldquo;Knowledge&amp;rdquo; in English. However, in a worldly sense, when we talk about knowledge, we usually refer to information about something—generally objects, people, processes, or events around us. Sometimes, it also refers to our own body; for a slightly deeper thinker, it includes the mind and ego as well. But for a spiritual seeker, this &amp;ldquo;something&amp;rdquo; is not an external thing or &amp;ldquo;thing&amp;rdquo; at all but the Self.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>How to Engage for Imparting Knowledge</title><link>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/how-to-engage-for-imparting-knowledge/</link><pubDate>Mon, 11 Jul 2022 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><author>hari@dasarpai.com (Dr. Hari Thapliyaal)</author><guid>https://dasarpai.github.io/wiaposts/how-to-engage-for-imparting-knowledge/</guid><description>&lt;p>
&lt;figure>
&lt;img class="my-0 rounded-md" loading="lazy" src="https://dasarpai.github.io/assets/images/wiapost/5193-How-To-Engage-For-Imparting-Knowledge.jpg" alt="How to Engage for Imparting Knowledge" />
&lt;/figure>
&lt;/p>
&lt;h1 class="relative group">How to Engage for Imparting Knowledge
&lt;div id="how-to-engage-for-imparting-knowledge" class="anchor">&lt;/div>
&lt;span
class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 ltr:-left-6 rtl:-right-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">
&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700"
style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#how-to-engage-for-imparting-knowledge" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>
&lt;/span>
&lt;/h1>
&lt;p>The biggest counterproductive assumption a teacher&lt;br>
or a trainer can make about the class is&lt;br>
&amp;ldquo;they all know what they want to learn and why they want to learn&amp;rdquo;.&lt;br>
If so, then the problem is already known.&lt;br>
Hence, let’s start with a solution and give gyan to these people.&lt;br>
But this assumption is wrong.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>